iI purchased an old HP workstation to use as a NAS and router at my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihome. This post is a short note of my process of setting it up.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Hardware Choice		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFor a NAS, you usually have these hardware choices:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Ready-to-use NAS (e.g. Synology)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Pros: ready to use out of the box.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Cons:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Expensive, to the extent of "free hardware for software		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      purchase".		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Harder to customize, when comparing the stock operating system		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      with various Linux distributions.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Second-hand servers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Pros:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Cheap. Most servers are thrown away by datacenters once their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      warranty ends, and are obtained at minimum cost, refurbished and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      then resold.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Stable. These servers are built to last, and are used in a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      datacenter with controlled temperature, humidity and no dust.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Cons：		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Noise. In order to lower the fan speed, you need to modify		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      system settings, replace with quieter fans, and/or install a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      separate fan speed controller.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Large (mainly concerning rack-mount servers).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Proprietary parts. Server manufacturers customize their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      components only for specific models. You will need to purchase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      these parts at extra cost if you want to extend your system.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Second-hand workstations		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Pros:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Cheap and stable, just like second-hand servers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Lower noise. After all, workstations are meant to be used near		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      office desktops rather than datacenters.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Cons:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Proprietary parts, same as second-hand servers.\\		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- DIY from regular PC parts		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Pros:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Customize to your exact need.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  - Cons:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Worse performance-to-price ratio compared to second-hand servers		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      and workstations.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    - Stability of customer-facing parts may be worse than		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      business-facing servers and workstations.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd I have these requirements for my NAS:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- I want to use Jellyfin video transcoding, H265 if possible. This		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  requires a 6th gen (Skylake) or newer Intel CPU with integrated		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  graphics, or an NVIDIA graphics card.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Other than that, I don't have any needs on performance (except very		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  low power CPUs like Intel Atom series).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Low noise. I'm currently living in a studio apartment, and the NAS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  will be in the same room where I sleep.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- I don't like ready-to-use NAS operating systems. I want to install		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  NixOS and customize it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- As cheap as it can get.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
