i## Video Transcoding		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs a SFF (small form factor) workstation, HP Z220 SFF can only use low		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprofile PCI-E expansion cards (with a height of 8cm) rather than		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istandard expansion cards (with a height of 12cm). In addition, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipower supply with a mere 240W output has no extra wiring for GPU power		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isupply, meaning that I cannot use GPUs with high performance and high		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipower consumption.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iInitially I purchased a NVIDIA Quadro P400 for $40, with a TDP of 30W.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe performance of this card is extremely weak, similar to the NVIDIA		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGT 1010 which few have heard off. It's even worse than a GT 1030!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, it comes with the same video encoding/decoding circuits as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe entire 10 series GPUs,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[and has support for H265 10-bit video encoding](https://developer.nvidia.com/video-encode-and-decode-gpu-support-matrix-new).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOther than different GPU core frequency, Quadro P400 has the exact		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isame video transcoding performance as other 10 series GPUs. Therefore,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iQuadro P400 is the choice of many NAS DIYers on Reddit.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAfter obtaining the GPU and testing it, I found that it can, indeed,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
itranscode 4K HEVC videos, at a speed of 60 FPS. But once I enable		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iJellyfin's tone-mapping feature, the transcoding speed lowers to 10-20		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFPS, causing stuttery video playback. Tone-mapping is used to convert		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe special color space (like HDR or Dolby Vision) to the standard SDR		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icolor space, so they can be correctly displayed on devices without HDR		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isupport. Jellyfin's tone-mapping implementation relies on GPU's 3D		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocessing units, and the Quadro P400 is quite lacking in 3D		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iperformance, causing the bottleneck.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI later replaced the GPU with a NVIDIA Tesla P4, with a TDP of 50W.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlthough it's a Tesla series card geared towards science computations,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit still has support for video transcoding, with the same circuits as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i10 series GPUs. This card sells on eBay for around $100, but since		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iit's passively cooled, you need to spend an extra $20 on fans and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ishrouds to cool it in a regular workstation.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTesting shows that this GPU can transcode videos to 4K 80Mbps at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iaround 60 FPS, with tone-mapping enabled. This completely satisfies my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
irequirement on video transcoding. The only downside is that, with no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istandard computer fan pinouts on the HP Z220 SFF motherboard, I have		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito power the fan with a USB 5V to 12V voltage step-up cable, and run		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe fan at maximum speed at all time. This creates a bit of noise, but		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI personally find it acceptable.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAs a bonus, NVIDIA Tesla P4 also supports NVIDIA GRID, creating		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual GPUs for virtual machines. But NVIDIA GRID requires a special		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ihost driver lacking 3D and video transcoding support, causing my		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iJellyfin video transcodes to fail. Therefore, I went with the regular		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU driver for now.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
